         <h2>Things that Annoy Me (The Grand Canyon Edition)</h2>
         <h2><small>by Adam Bodie</small></h2>
        <br>
        <br>
        <p>Imagine being on a trip of a lifetime at a popular National Park. Naturally, there are going to be a lot of people visiting, just like you. Many of them wind up in your pictures. No matter how hard you try, someone enters your picture
            (just as someone else leaves). Often times, you walk into someone else's picture. You try your best to wait, or to walk fast to avoid ruining that other person's moment. But what happens when you're walking and someone is blocking
            your path? Do you wait? Do you walk fast? Enter the Selfie Stick...</p>
        <p>Everyone loves to take selfies. It's easy, convenient and requires no stranger to get that special moment on camera for you. But it can only go the length of the longest arm you have. Enter the Selfie Stick, which can take selfies
            at a longer distance, to capture more stuff in the background. But what looks cool for the consumer is an eyesore for the passerby.</p>
        <p>No longer can a person walk between the camera and the object of affection. Instead, there's a goofy looking stick covering that space. You'd have to walk around a longer distance to get around the picture. And what if someone decided
            the moment you walk by that they want to use it? They'd have to swing it to set it up, making sure they don't hit you in the face. Some people, though, arent that careful. Bam! Now you got hit in the face with a stick. A great
            way to end your trip, with marks on your face from Selfie Sticks.</p>
        <p>Now I know what you're saying; Selfies are not going away, it's the 21st Century, yada yada yada. We guess what, there's a better solution then having some dorky looking stick take up so much space for the passerby. Have your loved
            one take a picture for you. Ask a stranger. Take a selfie without the stick. How much extra space do you really get in your photo? Chances are, you're not a good photographer to begin with. The picture is a little blurry because
            you can't stay still. Your finger winds up in the picture. You cut your head off like Hannibal Lecter. So please, leave the Selfie Stick at home and be thankful you can even have the technology to take a picture</p>
